		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f7af2682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>6:4.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Law—Statutes</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-2-220" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ice381ec074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-2-220</cite.query>
						<?page no="161"?>, the Georgia courts will take judicial notice of all public acts of the General Assembly of Georgia and of the United States[<footnote.reference refid="I783ce68074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] as well as the legislative journals of the Georgia General Assembly.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I783d0d9074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] In the past, when considering a constitutional question about an act of the General Assembly, a court would not take judicial notice of a statute with a notation of “as amended” or referenced by an unofficial citation.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I783d0d9174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] However, the Georgia Supreme Court overruled several cases to change this rule in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1980193591" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ice39f38274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Grantham v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I783d0d9274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] and extended Grantham in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1982119911" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ice3ab6d274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Wiggins v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I783d0d9374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] by holding that the court will consider a constitutional challenge where the statutory provision attacked is identified “with fair precision,” even without a citation.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
